      Oh Elon
   =20
 =20

In some parallel universe, Elon Musk=E2=80=99s dispute with Twitter Inc. is=
 about how many bots there are on Twitter. In that universe, Twitter=E2=80=
=99s merger agreement with Musk contains a representation=C2=A0that no more=
 than 5% of Twitter=E2=80=99s monetizable daily active users, or mDAUs, are=
 bots, Musk=E2=80=99s obligation to close the merger is contingent on this =
representation being true,=C2=A0and Musk has discovered that it is=C2=A0wro=
ng. Therefore he is able to walk away from the agreement, and maybe even su=
e Twitter for damages for misleading him.
In our actual universe none of this is true. In the real world, Musk signed=
 a merger agreement with Twitter, and it was publicly filed, and you can re=
ad it here. That merger agreement=C2=A0does not mention bots at all. In pur=
suing and signing this deal, Musk  was excited about =E2=80=9Cdefeating=E2=
=80=9D the bots, sure, but he didn=E2=80=99t care how many there were. (The=
 more of them there are, the more glory in defeating them.)=C2=A0He did not=
 do any due diligence on the number of bots before signing the agreement, n=
or did he ask Twitter to make any promises about how many=C2=A0bots there w=
ere. Nothing in the negotiations over the deal, or in the merger agreement =
itself, was in any way contingent on anything at all about bots.
Now, even in the real world, the merger agreement=C2=A0does=C2=A0contain a =
representation that none of Twitter=E2=80=99s filings with the US Securitie=
s and Exchange Commission=C2=A0=E2=80=9Ccontained any untrue statement of a=
 material fact.=E2=80=9D And if that representation is false enough to have=
 a =E2=80=9Cmaterial adverse effect=E2=80=9D on Twitter, then Musk can get =
out of the deal.
And Twitter=E2=80=99s SEC filings=C2=A0do=C2=A0mention bots. But they don=
=E2=80=99t=C2=A0contain any promises that no more than 5% of Twitter=E2=80=
=99s users are bots. These filings are also public, and you can also read t=
hem. Here is what they say about bots:
There are a number of false or spam accounts in existence on our platform.=
=C2=A0We have performed an internal review of a sample of accounts and esti=
mate that the average of false or spam accounts during the first quarter of=
 2022 represented fewer than 5% of our mDAU during the quarter. The false o=
r spam accounts for a period represents the average of false or spam accoun=
ts in the samples during each monthly analysis period during the quarter. I=
n making this determination, we applied significant judgment, so our estima=
tion of false or spam accounts may not accurately represent the actual numb=
er of such accounts, and the actual number of false or spam accounts could =
be higher than we have estimated.
Let=E2=80=99s pick out the factual assertions in that paragraph:
=09There are =E2=80=9Cfalse or spam accounts=E2=80=9D on Twitter.=09Twitter=
 reviews some sample accounts each month.=09It estimates, based on that rev=
iew,=C2=A0that the bots (false or spam accounts) are fewer than 5% of mDAUs=
.=09That estimate is based on the =E2=80=9Caverage of false or spam account=
s in the samples.=E2=80=9D=09That estimate, and the labeling of spam accoun=
ts, is subjective; Twitter =E2=80=9Capplied significant judgment=E2=80=9D t=
o reach it.=09=E2=80=9CThe actual number of false or spam accounts could be=
 higher than we have estimated.=E2=80=9D

You could imagine how some of those statements could be false.=C2=A0If Twit=
ter did not review any sample accounts =E2=80=94=C2=A0if it just made up th=
e 5% number and put it in the filings =E2=80=94=C2=A0then its SEC filings w=
ould be false. If it reviewed its samples and labeled 25% of them spam, and=
 then wrote 5% in the filings anyway, then the filings would be false.=C2=
=A0
On the other hand. If you said to Twitter =E2=80=9Clook, I don=E2=80=99t li=
ke how you sample accounts, and I really don=E2=80=99t like how you evaluat=
e them for spam.=C2=A0I have developed a better way to identify spam accoun=
ts, and when I apply my method to a different sample I conclude that 8% of =
your mDAUs are spam,=E2=80=9D and Twitter looked at your method and said =
=E2=80=9Coh, wow, you know what, you are entirely right in every respect, t=
his is better, 8% of our mDAUs are spam=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0then nothin=
g in Twitter=E2=80=99s SEC filings would be false. (I suppose they=E2=80=99=
d have to write something different in=C2=A0future=C2=A0filings.) The filin=
gs said that their numbers were estimates, that they applied significant ju=
dgment, and that the actual number might be higher. If you said =E2=80=9CI =
have a better estimate with better judgment, and the numbers are higher,=E2=
=80=9D they could reasonably respond =E2=80=9Cyes, right, exactly like we s=
aid.=E2=80=9D
Of course, if Twitter=E2=80=99s quarterly reports were wildly wrong about i=
ts operating or financial results, then that would be bad, even if Twitter =
prefaced those reports by saying =E2=80=9Chere=E2=80=99s our best guess but=
 we might be wrong.=E2=80=9D But the bot numbers, and the related numbers o=
f monetizable daily active users, are not part of Twitter=E2=80=99s financi=
al results. US generally accepted accounting principles do not cover bots o=
r mDAUs, and Twitter=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Ccalculation of mDAU is not based on=
 any standardized industry methodology and is not necessarily calculated in=
 the same manner or comparable to similarly titled measures presented by ot=
her companies.=E2=80=9D Nobody disputes that Twitter=E2=80=99s financial re=
sults =E2=80=94=C2=A0the amount of money it makes each quarter, etc. =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0are accurate. Twitter discloses its mDAU numbers to help investors=
 understand how its managers =E2=80=9Cevaluate our business, measure our pe=
rformance, identify trends affecting our business, formulate business plans=
 and make strategic decisions.=E2=80=9D One quite live possibility is that =
Twitter=E2=80=99s managers are=C2=A0bad=C2=A0at evaluating their business, =
formulating business plans and making strategic decisions. This would not m=
ake their disclosures wrong, however.
Elon Musk is  trying to get out of his deal to buy Twitter. He claims to=C2=
=A0believe=C2=A0that more than 5% of Twitter=E2=80=99s mDAUs are bots. It w=
ould clearly be advantageous for Musk if we lived in the alternate universe=
 where Twitter=E2=80=99s merger agreement promised that no more than 5% of =
its mDAUs were bots. For one thing, he might be right, and then he could ge=
t out of the deal. He has never produced even a hint of any evidence that h=
e might be right, but never mind!=C2=A0In any case there could be a complic=
ated factual dispute: Twitter could argue for its numbers and its methodolo=
gy, and Musk could argue for different numbers using a different methodolog=
y, and it would be fairly easy to muddy the waters and create the=C2=A0impr=
ession=C2=A0that Musk could be right.=C2=A0 Musk is good at muddying waters=
 and impressing the impressionable, and this would play to his strengths. W=
hereas in the real world, where Twitter did not promise Musk that fewer tha=
n 5% of mDAUs are bots, it is much harder for Musk to make any argument at =
all that he can get out of his deal.
On Friday, Musk=E2=80=99s lawyers filed a document in the Delaware Chancery=
 Court opposing Twitter=E2=80=99s motion to have a quick trial in September=
 on Musk=E2=80=99s efforts to get out of the deal. This document is forcefu=
l and well-done,
  [1]
=C2=A0but it exists in that alternate universe where Twitter promised that =
no more than 5% of its mDAUs are spam bots and Musk agreed to buy Twitter i=
n reliance on that promise. =E2=80=9CTwitter also represents that no more t=
han 5% of these accounts in a given quarter consist of false or spam accoun=
ts,=E2=80=9D say Musk=E2=80=99s lawyers, even though, as I have just explai=
ned in incredibly boring detail, Twitter does not say that at all anywhere.=
=C2=A0
In Musk=E2=80=99s universe, (1) Twitter promised him that fewer than 5% of =
mDAUs are bots, (2) he believed them when he signed the deal, (3) he stoppe=
d believing them and asked for proof, and (4) they stonewalled him instead =
of providing proof. But if you just look at what the merger agreement and t=
he SEC filings=C2=A0actually=C2=A0say, the whole thing is nonsense.=C2=A0Mu=
sk=E2=80=99s lawyers say:
In a May 6 meeting with Twitter executives, Musk was flabbergasted to learn=
 just how meager Twitter=E2=80=99s process was. Human reviewers randomly sa=
mpled 100 accounts per day (less than 0.00005% of daily users) and applied =
unidentified standards to somehow conclude every quarter for nearly three y=
ears that fewer than 5% of Twitter users were false or spam. That=E2=80=99s=
 it. No automation, no AI, no machine learning.
And again (citations omitted):

Thus, on May 6, 2022, Musk met with Twitter=E2=80=99s leadership,=C2=A0incl=
uding its CEO and CFO to discuss, among other items, how Twitter calculates=
 its spam population.
Musk was stunned to discover that Twitter=E2=80=99s process for identifying=
 spam accounts relied on human reviewers to eyeball a minuscule portion of =
the userbase rather than utilizing the company=E2=80=99s machine learning c=
apabilities. Musk quickly understood that management did not have a handle =
on the bot and spam issue.

But this concedes the whole ballgame! Just from reading this, you know that=
:
=09Every sentence about bots in Twitter=E2=80=99s SEC filings is true. Twit=
ter does in fact estimate the bot numbers by sampling some accounts (=E2=80=
=9Ca minuscule portion of the userbase=E2=80=9D) and applying judgment (=E2=
=80=9Crelied on human reviewers to eyeball=E2=80=9D) to determine which of =
them are bots, and then uses the average number of bots in its samples to e=
stimate the total number of bots. That estimate is under 5%. There are no m=
isrepresentations about bots in the SEC filings, which accurately describe =
the process that Twitter explained to Musk and that Musk believes Twitter f=
ollows.=C2=A0There are no misrepresentations about bots in the merger agree=
ment, because there are no representations about bots at all in the merger =
agreement.=C2=A0=09Musk asked for information about how Twitter calculates =
its bot numbers, and Twitter gave him the information he needed. Musk knows=
 exactly how Twitter calculates its bot numbers! So do you! It is set out i=
n that quote from Musk=E2=80=99s lawyers. He just  doesn=E2=80=99t like it.=
 So he=C2=A0followed up by asking for tons and tons of data to do his own c=
alculations, and Twitter gave him some but not all of what=C2=A0he asked fo=
r. But this data was totally irrelevant both to Twitter=E2=80=99s represent=
ations (which were true) and to closing the deal (because Musk is trying=C2=
=A0not=C2=A0to close the deal), so Twitter   had no obligation to give it t=
o him.

Instead, the point here=C2=A0is that Musk believes that he has=C2=A0better =
ideas=C2=A0for how to count and combat spam bots. I am not at all sure that=
=E2=80=99s true =E2=80=94=C2=A0there=E2=80=99s no particular reason to thin=
k that checking 3,000 random accounts per month produces=C2=A0an insufficie=
nt sample, or that human classification will be=C2=A0worse at identifying b=
ots than =E2=80=9Cmachine learning=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 but never mind.
  [2]
=C2=A0Let=E2=80=99s just concede it. Let=E2=80=99s all agree that Musk does=
 have better ideas for how to count and combat spam bots on Twitter. Oooh, =
machine learning! Super!=C2=A0THAT=E2=80=99S=C2=A0WHY HE WANTED TO BUY THE =
COMPANY! =E2=80=9CManagement did not have a handle on the bot and spam issu=
e=E2=80=9D was his=C2=A0reason=C2=A0for thinking that he could do a better =
job and extract more value from Twitter! =E2=80=9CI don=E2=80=99t have conf=
idence in management nor do I believe I can drive the necessary change in t=
he public market,=E2=80=9D said Musk, to Twitter, when he demanded to take =
the company private at $54.20 per share.
  [3]
=C2=A0
The idea that Musk could fling some machine learning at the bots is very re=
levant to Musk=E2=80=99s theory, from way back in April, that he was the be=
st person to own Twitter and therefore should pressure Twitter into selling=
 to him at a premium to its market price. It is arguably relevant to the al=
ternate-universe dispute in which a court would have to decide how many bot=
s Twitter has.
But it is=C2=A0irrelevant to the actual=C2=A0dispute in our universe, which=
 is about whether Twitter made any misrepresentations in its merger agreeme=
nt with=C2=A0Musk.=C2=A0It did not. Musk would like to have a better spam-c=
ounting and spam-fighting system, which he is free to do, as soon as he clo=
ses the merger and owns Twitter. There is no simply no dispute here at all.
  [4]

Musk=E2=80=99s lawyers would=C2=A0like=C2=A0to make this case into a compli=
cated factual dispute over spam bots. A complicated factual dispute will=C2=
=A0take longer; you=E2=80=99ll need more witnesses and experts and discover=
y about how many bots there are. Taking longer is to Musk=E2=80=99s advanta=
ge. For one thing, it will increase the pressure on Twitter, which will hav=
e this uncertainty hanging out there, weighing on its stock price and opera=
tions, making it more likely to give up and settle. For another thing, Musk=
=E2=80=99s financing commitments expire in April 2023; if he can push the c=
onclusion of this case past then, then he won=E2=80=99t have financing, so =
he =E2=80=94=C2=A0arguably =E2=80=94=C2=A0can=E2=80=99t be forced to close =
the deal.
  [5]

And so Musk=E2=80=99s lawyers want to delay the trial so they can fish for =
evidence and get a bunch of experts to testify about bot-counting:

The core dispute over false and spam accounts is fundamental to Twitter=E2=
=80=99s value. It is also extremely fact and expert intensive, requiring su=
bstantial time for discovery. =E2=80=A6
Defendants anticipate that these issues will require at least 30-40 fact de=
positions, and at least 12 expert depositions in total. These include fact =
depositions of the principals and advisors that negotiated the merger, top =
management, board members, data science and audit personnel familiar with=
=C2=A0Twitter=E2=80=99s spam and false account detection procedures, financ=
e and advertising executives, and executives knowledgeable about Twitter=E2=
=80=99s operational changes. It will also require 30(b)(6) depositions of w=
itnesses who can explain Twitter=E2=80=99s information systems and processe=
s for identifying spam and false accounts, as well as its procedures and co=
ntrols governing Twitter=E2=80=99s disclosures. Experts may include adverti=
sing, data science, valuation, finance, and industry experts. =E2=80=A6
Indeed, this case goes well beyond the significant complexities of a typica=
l =E2=80=9Cbusted deal=E2=80=9D case, implicating complex data science ques=
tions concerning the accuracy of Twitter=E2=80=99s disclosures regarding th=
e number of false and spam accounts. The factual record regarding these rep=
resentations will likely involve sifting through hundreds of billions of ac=
tions on Twitter and reviewing related sampling and control processes.=C2=
=A0Just the time it will take to load, process and analyze the hundreds of =
terabytes of relevant data will exceed Plaintiff=E2=80=99s hasty schedule.

Again, if you wanted to have a trial on the question =E2=80=9Chow many Twit=
ter users are bots,=E2=80=9D you would probably want to bring in=C2=A0a bun=
ch of bot-counting experts and cross-examine them and sift data and stuff. =
But you absolutely don=E2=80=99t need that to determine if Twitter=E2=80=99=
s SEC filings are true. The filings say that Twitter uses =E2=80=9Csignific=
ant judgment=E2=80=9D and could be wrong. If you get an expert to testify t=
hat, in her expert opinion, Twitter should have used some different method =
and gotten a different number, you are just agreeing that the disclosure is=
 correct. The expert=E2=80=99s testimony is irrelevant.=C2=A0
On Tuesday,  there will be a hearing on Twitter=E2=80=99s motion to expedit=
e the case and have a trial in September, which Musk is opposing. (He wants=
 a trial in February 2023.)=C2=A0That hearing=C2=A0will not=C2=A0decide=C2=
=A0the case or anything, but it will set the tone in important ways. If the=
 judge, Delaware Chancellor Kathaleen McCormick, agrees with Musk that this=
 should=C2=A0be a fact-intensive trial in which dozens of experts will have=
 to testify about how to count bots, then she will probably delay=C2=A0the =
trial until 2023. That will be very good for Musk: the delay, but also the =
focus on=C2=A0bot-counting. If she agrees with Twitter that this should=C2=
=A0be a straightforward trial about what the merger agreement says and whet=
her Musk has to do it, then she will probably set the trial for September, =
and that will be very good for Twitter.=C2=A0
This is extremely dumb and I wish I had not written it. But I feel like alm=
ost everything that I see about this dispute takes place in the alternate u=
niverse, the one where Twitter and Musk are going to court to determine onc=
e and for all how many bots there are. They just aren=E2=80=99t. In our act=
ual universe, Twitter has made only extremely cautious and limited represen=
tations about=C2=A0how it counts bots. And=C2=A0Musk is mad that the bot-co=
unters didn=E2=80=99t count bots the way he wanted them to. He met with Twi=
tter=E2=80=99s management, and they explained how they count bots, and he w=
as horrified. He came away from their meeting thinking that he could do a b=
etter job of fighting spam at Twitter, by sprinkling some machine learning =
on the spam or whatever. That=E2=80=99s great! That=E2=80=99s why he wanted=
 to buy Twitter! And why he should have to!
