in your inbox, please=C2=A0subscribe at this link. Or you can subscribe to =
Money Stuff and other great Bloomberg newsletters here. Thanks!
       =20
  [1] In particular it does a good job of arguing that Musk=E2=80=99s conce=
rn about bots is *genuine*, driven not by the market=E2=80=99s decline over=
 the last few months (which makes this deal look more expensive and less at=
tractive to Musk) but by real concern about Twitter=E2=80=99s ability to co=
unt bots. As I argue in the text, I don=E2=80=99t think this is particularl=
y relevant to Musk=E2=80=99s obligation to close the deal, but it does make=
 his position more sympathetic. In his lawyers=E2=80=99 telling, his concer=
ns were triggered not by the market drop but by Twitter=E2=80=99s disclosur=
e, three days after signing, that it had incorrectly calculated some of its=
 daily active user numbers for years. The mistake was big enough to require=
 updating the historical numbers, though small enough that even Musk=E2=80=
=99s lawyers don=E2=80=99t argue that it was material to the deal. (Some qu=
arterly counts were off by about 1%.) We talked about this restatement  at =
the time, and I explained that it was obviously not big enough to be a =E2=
=80=9Cmaterial adverse effect=E2=80=9D that could get Musk out of the deal,=
 and it looks like his lawyers agree. But I also said that, if Twitter knew=
 about the mistake before the merger agreement was signed =E2=80=94 which s=
eemed likely to me, since they disclosed it publicly just three days later =
=E2=80=94 then they should have disclosed it to Musk before signing the dea=
l. But his filing says they didn=E2=80=99t: =E2=80=9COn April 28, just thre=
e days after signing the Agreement, Twitter restated three years of its mDA=
U numbers, despite never disclosing the issue to Defendants pre-signing.=E2=
=80=9D I =E2=80=A6 that=E2=80=99s weird? They should have disclosed that?=
=20


  [2] Musk=E2=80=99s lawyers don=E2=80=99t argue that automation or AI or m=
achine learning would be better or anything; they just expect everyone to t=
hink =E2=80=9Coh of course, AI.=E2=80=9D Presumably you would use human jud=
gment to train the AI? But, sure, if you want to decide whose approach is b=
etter, you would need to examine facts and talk to experts and get a sense =
of the debate. My point is that there is no reason for the court to care wh=
ose approach is better, because that simply isn=E2=80=99t relevant to anyon=
e=E2=80=99s obligations under the merger agreement.


  [3] Similarly, one of Musk=E2=80=99s lawyers=E2=80=99 letters to Twitter =
from May =E2=80=94 included in Twitter=E2=80=99s latest revised proxy state=
ment =E2=80=94 says that =E2=80=9CMr. Musk was surprised to learn of the la=
x methodologies that Twitter employs to assess the actual prevalence of fak=
e or spam accounts on its platform,=E2=80=9D and that =E2=80=9CMr. Musk req=
uested that Twitter apply more rigorous computer-aided and third-party test=
ing to determine the prevalence of fake or spam accounts on its platform wi=
th greater certainty.=E2=80=9D Again, that is totally a thing that he can d=
o, when he buys Twitter: If he owns the company, he is free to tell it how =
to run its business. He just has to buy it first.=20


  [4] There  is also a dispute about whether Twitter breached its  informat=
ion covenant by not giving Musk all the information he wants about bots, bu=
t that is in an important sense downstream of the dispute about misrepresen=
tations. Nobody really pretends that Musk was asking for information to hel=
p him close the deal, which is what the information covenant is actually fo=
r. Instead, Musks=E2=80=99 lawyers argue that he =E2=80=9Cexercised [his] i=
nformation rights to validate Twitter=E2=80=99s user claims=E2=80=9D =E2=80=
=94 that is, to check if Twitter=E2=80=99s representations are true. If you=
 notice that Musk effectively concedes that the representations are true, t=
hen these information demands are irrelevant. There is also a dispute about=
 whether Twitter was operating =E2=80=9Cin the ordinary course=E2=80=9D whe=
n it fired a couple of employees; Musk=E2=80=99s lawyers seem pretty half-h=
earted about this one but it is still a live controversy I suppose.


  [5] We talked  here and  here about potential remedies in this case. The =
short version is that if the judge concludes that Musk has no right to term=
inate the merger agreement, then she can either make him pay $1 billion of =
damages (but no more) or force him to close the deal (=E2=80=9Cspecific per=
formance=E2=80=9D). A $1 billion award is effectively a win for Musk; it ge=
ts him out of his deal cheap, whereas paying $44 billion to buy Twitter is =
expensive. The merger agreement says, however, that he can=E2=80=99t be for=
ced into specific performance unless his $13 billion of debt financing is a=
vailable, and the debt financing commitments have an outside date of April =
25, 2023. Musk wants a trial in February 2023; with a bit of luck and delay=
 that could push a verdict past when the financing expires, giving him anot=
her excuse to walk away. This is not airtight =E2=80=94 we  talked the othe=
r day about a 2021 decision by Chancellor McCormick, the judge in this case=
, ordering specific performance in a similar case even though the buyer=E2=
=80=99s financing was not available, on the theory that the buyer had inten=
tionally torpedoed the financing and could not use that as an excuse. Still=
, might as well try.


